<h1>Ser &amp; Estar</h1>
<div class="slide-deck" id="slide-deck">
<div class="slide"><div class="slide-card"><div class="slide-header"><h2>Two Ways to Say 'To Be'</h2></div><p class="slide-explanation">In Spanish, there are two verbs meaning '<b>to be</b>': <b>ser</b> and <b>estar</b>. You must choose the correct one depending on the meaning. For example: <b>Yo soy</b> (I am) vs <b>Yo estoy</b> (I am).</p><div class="watch-out">English uses 'am/is/are' for everything. Spanish splits 'to be' into two verbs.</div></div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="slide-card"><div class="slide-header"><h2>Using Ser for Permanent Traits</h2></div><p class="slide-explanation">Use <b>ser</b> for things that are <b>permanent</b> or <b>essential</b>: identity, nationality, profession, physical description. Examples: <b>Yo soy Ana</b> (I am Ana), <b>Él es español</b> (He is Spanish), <b>Ella es doctora</b> (She is a doctor).</p><div class="watch-out">If it's a core part of a person or thing, choose ser.</div></div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="slide-card"><div class="slide-header"><h2>Using Estar for Temporary States</h2></div><p class="slide-explanation">Use <b>estar</b> for <b>temporary conditions</b> or <b>locations</b>: feelings, health, weather, position. Examples: <b>Yo estoy cansado</b> (I am tired), <b>El libro está en la mesa</b> (The book is on the table), <b>Hoy está nublado</b> (Today is cloudy).</p><div class="watch-out">If the state can change, use estar.</div></div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="slide-card"><div class="slide-header"><h2>Conjugation of Ser</h2></div><p class="slide-explanation">Present tense of <b>ser</b>: yo <b>soy</b>, tú <b>eres</b>, él/ella/usted <b>es</b>, nosotros <b>somos</b>, vosotros <b>sois</b>, ellos/ellas/ustedes <b>son</b>. Example: <b>Nosotros somos amigos</b> (We are friends).</p><div class="watch-out">Memorise these forms – they are irregular.</div></div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="slide-card"><div class="slide-header"><h2>Conjugation of Estar</h2></div><p class="slide-explanation">Present tense of <b>estar</b>: yo <b>estoy</b>, tú <b>estás</b>, él/ella/usted <b>está</b>, nosotros <b>estamos</b>, vosotros <b>estáis</b>, ellos/ellas/ustedes <b>están</b>. Example: <b>Ellos están contentos</b> (They are happy).</p><div class="watch-out">Notice the accent marks on estás, está, están.</div></div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="slide-card"><div class="slide-header"><h2>Quick Memory Trick</h2></div><p class="slide-explanation">Use the acronyms: <b>DOCTOR</b> for ser (Description, Occupation, Characteristic, Time, Origin, Relation). Use <b>PLACE</b> for estar (Position, Location, Action, Condition, Emotion). For A1, remember: <b>how you feel and where you are, always use estar</b>.</p><div class="watch-out">You will learn more exceptions at higher levels.</div></div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="slide-card"><div class="slide-header"><h2>Common Mistakes</h2></div><p class="slide-explanation">Mistake 1: <b>Yo estoy feliz</b> (correct) vs <b>Yo soy feliz</b> (incorrect for temporary happiness – use ser only for 'happy person' as a trait). Mistake 2: <b>La manzana es verde</b> (if it's always green) vs <b>La manzana está verde</b> (if it is unripe – temporary). At A1, avoid using ser for location: <b>El museo es en Madrid</b> (wrong) – say <b>El museo está en Madrid</b>.</p></div></div>
